            <br/>
            <br/>
            <br/>
            <h6>
              Mazzara S et al.
              <a target="_blank" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/srep45477">
                <b>CombiROC: an interactive web tool for selecting accurate marker combinations of omics data.</b>
              </a>
              This application was created by the
              <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ingm.org/en/research/facilities/protein-microarray">Protein Microarray</a>
               and 
              <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ingm.org/en/research/facilities/bioinformatics">Bioinformatics</a>
               units at INGM. If you have questions or comments, please contact Saveria Mazzara (saveria.mazzara(at)gmail.com). This application was implemented using shiny (for web interface) and other additional R packages (for data manipulation).
            </h6>
          </div>
          <div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="shiny-tab-FAQ">
            <div>
              <div class="box box-solid box-info">
                <div class="box-header">
                  <h3 class="box-title">FAQ</h3>
                </div>
                <div class="box-body">
                  <a href="#q1">
                    <h4>Q: Can I use combiROC to screen for biomarkers?</h4>
                  </a>
                  <p align="justify">CombiROC is not a screening tool. You should be able to select your potential biomarkers using traditional screening methodologies such as differential expression for genes, microRNA or proteins by arrays, sequencing or mass spec. Once you have shortlisted a number of potential biomarkers, i.e. your "signature", you can explore the performance of their combinations with CombiROC</p>
                  <a href="#q2">
                    <h4>Q: How many biomarkers can CombiROC handle?</h4>
                  </a>
                  <p align="justify">There is no theoretic limit to the number of biomarkers. Practically a limit is imposed by computational load given by  big numbers: "n" markers can combine in "2^n -1" way (i.e. 31 combinations of 5 markers; 1032 combinations of 10 markers; more than 1 nonillion combinations for 100 markers). Thus CombiROC best performs for marker lists composed of up to 10 markers, which is a reasonable and sufficiently high number of potential biomarkers in the clinical practice.</p>
                  <a href="#q3">
                    <h4>Q: Are there hard thresholds to set up?</h4>
                  </a>
                  <p align="justify">There are no mandatory hard threshold to set up after uploading the data. Nevertheless, the application asks the user to "set the test signal cutoff" (in the Analysis / Combinatorial analysis step), which is strictly inherent to each and every dataset uploaded and is aimed at eliminating the noise from the signal under the technical detection thresholds given by the specific experimental methods used. The user can virtually set this threshold equal to the minimum value in the dataset (no zeroes are allowed) or, better, extimate a "true" signal value observing the value distributions in the box plot panels and the relative box plot statistics generated by the app after the data have been uploaded.</p>
                  <a href="#q4">
                    <h4>Q: When should I use the preprocessing tab?</h4>
                  </a>
                  <p align="justify">The choice of data prepreocessing depends on the biological/clinical data under investigation. In general, the aim of this optional step is to facilitate data analysis and model intepretation removing instrumental noise and making the measurements of the samples comparable.</p>
                  <ul><li> For example, a variable/biomarker could contain one or few extreme measurements which may dominate over the other measurements; in other words, this variable/marker departs from normality. One way to achieve a more symmetric data distribution is by transforamtion such as the "log-transformation".</li>
                        <li>Data scaling is equivalent to giving all of the variables equal importance, hence this procedure could be particularly useful in "omics" datasets where variables are characterized by large scale effects. There are nmany ways to scale the data, but the most common technique is the "unit variance" or the "pareto scaling".</li>
                        </ul>
                  <a href="#q5">
                    <h4>Q: Can I customize the name of markers in the header of my file?</h4>
                  </a>
                  <p align="justify">Unfortunately, not yet. This first public version of CombiROC is able to 
correctly handle only datasets whose markers in the header are named with "Marker1", "Marker2", ... , "MarkerN". </p>
                  <a href="#q6">
                    <h4>Q: What happens if I don't put any SE/SP cutoff in the Gold Combination bubble plot step?</h4>
                  </a>
                  <p align="justify">You do not necessarily have to raise the SE/SP filtering cutoffs in the gold combination step. If you don't put any cutoff all the possible combinations will be considered as "gold" and will be taken further in the analysis. Raising the cutoffs allows you to shortlist to the best performing ones.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <br/>
            <br/>
